The grant provided travel support for American participants of the following five School-conferences:

-- the first two "Hyperbolic Dynamics, Large Deviations and Fluctuations"  and "Large deviations and thermodynamical formalis" were part of a semester-long program "Hyperbolic Dynamics, Large Deviations and Fluctuations" that took place at the Centre Interfacultaire Bernoulli, EPF Lausanne, Switzerland in Spring 2013;

-- "Dynamical Systems and Geometry", Marseille -- Lumini, France, March 2014;

-- "Houston Summer School on Dynamical Systems", Houston, TX, May 2014; 

-- "Probability in Dynamics", Rio-de-Janeiro, Brazil, May 2014.



During the last 50 years statistical properties of dynamical systems of various types and in many different situations have been a subject of extensive study in statistical mechanics and thermodynamics, ergodic and probability theories, and some areas of mathematical physics. The results of this study have had a profound effect on a whole lot of areas in mathematics, physics, engineering and biology.



Intellectual Merit: The school-conferences provided a plethora of activities and a meeting place for mathematicians from around the globe working in dynamical systems and related topics. They were also a forum for both young and established researchers to exchange ideas with their counterparts throughout the world. The mini-courses were given by distinguished mathematicians, well-known experts in the field of dynamical systems. Thus, these events promoted current and future research and created a concrete agenda for further research on several fronts. 


Broader Impact. The school-conferences were focused on the development and support of young mathematicians who learned and interacted directly with leading researchers and were also exposed to discuss and collaborate with distinguished participants. All participants, including members of traditionally underrepresented groups  benefited highly from the presence of many strong young mathematicians from Europe and Latin America. 



